{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FCET6CAacr76vkwLJwXc2U","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012wnetNN5Kc9VVYGPgMwugk","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"theorem_title":"Heat equation uniqueness by the energy method","theorem_statement":"Let \(u,v\) be sufficiently regular solutions of the heat equation on \((0,L)\times[0,T]\) satisfying \(u_t=u_{xx}\), \(v_t=v_{xx}\), with the same initial data \(u(x,0)=v(x,0)\) and homogeneous Dirichlet boundary conditions \(u(0,t)=u(L,t)=v(0,t)=v(L,t)=0\). Then \(u=v\) on \([0,L]\times[0,T]\).","root_node_id":"heat_uniqueness","nodes":"[
  {
    "id": "energy_dissipation",
    "title": "Energy is nonincreasing: \(E'(t) \le 0\)",
    "informal_statement": "Let \(w = u - v\) satisfy \(w_t = w_{xx}\) on \((0,L)\times(0,T)\) with \(w(0,t)=w(L,t)=0\), and define the energy \(E(t) = \tfrac{1}{2}\int_0^L w(x,t)^2\,dx\). Then \(E'(t) = -\int_0^L |w_x(x,t)|^2\,dx \le 0\) for all \(t \in [0,T]\).",
    "informal_proof_text": "Differentiating under the integral sign (justified by the assumed regularity of \(w\)):\n\\[\nE'(t) = \\int_0^L w\\, w_t\\,dx.\n\\]\nSubstituting the PDE \(w_t = w_{xx}\\):\n\\[\nE'(t) = \\int_0^L w\\, w_{xx}\\,dx.\n\\]\nIntegrating by parts in \(x\\):\n\\[\n\\int_0^L w\\, w_{xx}\\,dx = \\bigl[w\\, w_x\\bigr]_{0}^{L} - \\int_0^L |w_x|^2\\,dx.\n\\]\nThe boundary term vanishes because \(w(0,t) = w(L,t) = 0\\), so\n\\[\nE'(t) = -\\int_0^L |w_x(x,t)|^2\\,dx \\le 0.\n\\]",
    "display_label": "\(E'(t) = -\\int_0^L |w_x|^2\\,dx \\le 0\)"
  },
  {
    "id": "heat_uniqueness",
    "title": "Heat equation uniqueness by the energy method",
    "informal_statement": "Under the stated hypotheses, \(u = v\) on \([0,L]\\times[0,T]\\).",
    "informal_proof_text": "Set \(w = u - v\\). Then \(w\\) satisfies \(w_t = w_{xx}\\) on \((0,L)\\times(0,T)\\) with zero initial data \(w(x,0)=0\\) and zero Dirichlet boundary conditions \(w(0,t)=w(L,t)=0\\).\n\nDefine \(E(t) = \\tfrac{1}{2}\\int_0^L w(x,t)^2\\,dx\\). By the energy dissipation lemma, \(E'(t) \\le 0\\), so \(E\\) is nonincreasing. At \(t=0\\), \(w(x,0)=0\\) gives \(E(0) = 0\\). Since \(E(t) \\ge 0\\) by definition and \(E\\) is nonincreasing from \(0\\), we conclude \(E(t) = 0\\) for all \(t \\in [0,T]\\).\n\nHence \(\\int_0^L w(x,t)^2\\,dx = 0\\) for all \(t\\), so \(w(x,t) = 0\\) for all \((x,t)\\), i.e., \(u = v\\).",
    "display_label": "Heat uniqueness (energy method)"
  }
]","edges":[{"source_id":"energy_dissipation","target_id":"heat_uniqueness","label":"used by","explanation":"The nonincreasing property E'(t) ≤ 0 together with E(0)=0 and E(t)≥0 forces E(t)=0 for all t, which is the key step in the root proof."}],"candidates":[{"node_id":"energy_dissipation","priority":1,"rationale":"This node contains the entire technical core of the proof: differentiation under the integral, PDE substitution, the integration-by-parts identity, and the cancellation of boundary terms. It is a concrete, self-contained computation that is directly formalizable and carries the main inferential load of the argument."},{"node_id":"heat_uniqueness","priority":2,"rationale":"The root theorem is the natural top-level Lean statement. Once energy_dissipation is formalized, the remaining steps—E(0)=0, monotonicity forcing E≡0, and pointwise vanishing of w—are straightforward and can be verified efficiently, making the full root a good secondary candidate."}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2984,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2984},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fb873c14-f1af-45c6-8f6c-bf6d78c1ea75","uuid":"986fdd8b-8324-4c5d-923e-2805b8855fbb"}
